}\n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 1428\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_05.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Aug 22, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Dover''' is a small town in [[Pope County, Arkansas]], United States. The population was 1,378 at the [[United States Census 2010|2010 census]]. It is part of the [[Russellville, Arkansas|Russellville]] [[Russellville micropolitan area|Micropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n== Geography ==\nDover is located at {{Coord|35|24|2|N|93|6|45|W|type:city}} (35.400597, -93.112534).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|1.8|sqmi|km2}}, all land.\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 368\n|1890= 528\n|1900= 373\n|1910= 385\n|1920= 388\n|1930= 510\n|1940= 493\n|1950= 510\n|1960= 525\n|1970= 662\n|1980= 948\n|1990= 1055\n|2000= 1329\n|2010= 1378\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=1428\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2020-02-12 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder }}</ref> of 2000, there were 1,329 people, 529 households, and 372 families residing in the city.  The [[population density]] was 732.7 people per square mile (283.5/km\u00b2).  There were 579 housing units at an average density of 319.2 per square mile (123.5/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 97.37% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 0.23% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.68% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.15% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.60% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.98% from two or more races.  1.96% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 529 households out of which 37.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 16.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 29.5% were non-families. 26.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.50 and the average family size was 3.01.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 29.3% under the age of 18, 10.2% from 18 to 24, 28.1% from 25 to 44, 18.6% from 45 to 64, and 13.8% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 32 years. For every 100 females, there were 79.8 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 79.0 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $27,697, and the median income for a family was $33,879. Males had a median income of $25,625 versus $19,073 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $13,261. About 10.6% of families and 14.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 13.9% of those under age 18 and 14.0% of those age 65 or over.\n\n== General info ==\nDover was either named by British aristocrats in the 1830s for [[Dover|Dover, Kent, England]] or by Stephen Rye in 1832 for [[Dover, Tennessee]].<ref>{{Cite book | last = Deane | first = Ernie | authorlink = Ernie Deane | title = Arkansas Place Names | publisher = The Ozarks Mountaineer | year = 1986 | location = Branson, Missouri | pages = 83 }}</ref> Dover was the county seat for Pope County in the 1800s. The original Pope County Courthouse was located where Dover Supermarket now sits. Dover is a small town near [[Russellville, Arkansas|Russellville]]; it has several churches, a grocery store and a hardware store. Dover acts like a satellite city in relation to nearby Russellville{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}} and many residents commute regularly for work and education.\n\nOn June 3, 1998 a Bible dated to 1283 was discovered on the grounds of a church in Dover and gained brief notoriety as the \"Dover Bible,\" with local religious leaders citing it as \"irrefutable proof of Christ's mission in the Americas.\" The Dover Bible, however, was eventually found to be a hoax after undergoing examination by students at [[Arkansas Tech University]] in nearby [[Russellville, AR]], who determined the copy to be loosely based on the King James Bible and inconsistent with thirteenth century language and composition. Its current condition and whereabouts are unknown.\n\n== The Dover massacre ==\n{{unsourced|section|date=March 2020}}\nOn December 22 and 26, 1987, [[Ronald Gene Simmons]], of near Dover, killed all fourteen members of his family during a [[Christmas]] reunion at the Simmons property 6.5 miles north of Dover. Two days later, he continued his killing spree in the county seat of [[Russellville, Arkansas|Russellville]], having targeted previous employers and co-workers, killing two and wounding two more. Simmons was arrested without resistance, was [[Capital punishment|sentenced to death]] on December 10, 1989, and executed on June 25, 1990, the quickest sentence-to-execution time in the United States since the death penalty was reinstated in 1976.\n\n== Notable people ==\n\n* [[Robert Dale (politician)|Robert E. Dale]], Republican former member of the [[Arkansas House of Representatives]] from Dover, 2009 to 2015\n* [[Jeff Davis (Arkansas governor)|Jeff Davis]], 20th [[Governor of Arkansas]] (1901-1907), later a [[United States Senate|US Senator]] (1907-1913). Davis was known for demagoguery and fiery rhetoric to appeal to his agrarian political base while disparaging city dwellers, blacks and Yankees\n* [[Trevor Drown]], Republican member of the Arkansas House of Representatives for Pope and Van Buren counties since 2015; succeeded Robert Dale \n* [[Ronald Gene Simmons]], retired United States Air Force master sergeant who killed sixteen people over a weeklong period in 1987, beginning in Dover\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{Pope County, Arkansas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Pope County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Russellville, Arkansas micropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1832]]\n[[Category:1832 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Kobra98", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dover,_Arkansas"}
{"title_page": "John Edwards (English Labour politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2015}}\n{{more footnotes|date=October 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''Lewis John Edwards''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (27 May 1904 \u2013 23 November 1959) was a British university lecturer, [[trade union]] leader and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician.\n\n==Life and career==\nEdwards was born in [[Aylesbury]], the son of a railwayman, and educated at the [[Aylesbury Grammar School]]. After working for a bank, he studied for the priesthood at the [[College of the Resurrection|College of the Resurrection, Mirfield]], but decided his vocation lay outside the church. He then completed a degree in Economics at [[Leeds University]].\n\nHe became a staff tutor at the [[University of Leeds]] and lectured in economics for the [[Workers Educational Association]]. He was elected to [[Leeds City Council]], and after working in a university appointment in [[Birmingham]], he became secretary for adult education at [[Liverpool University]].\n\nWhile at Liverpool, he was elected general secretary of the [[Post Office Engineering Union]]. He was elected as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Blackburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]] in the [[United Kingdom]] [[1945 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1945]]. He became [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Stafford Cripps]] at the [[Board of Trade]], and then in 1947 he was made [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Ministry of Health]]. He carried through Parliament the [[National Assistance Act 1948]], which abolished the remaining parts of the [[Poor Law]], an achievement of which he was particularly proud.\n\nIn 1949 he returned to the Board of Trade as [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Board of Trade|Parliamentary Secretary]], supporting the President, [[Harold Wilson]]. In the [[1950 United Kingdom general election|election of 1950]] he lost his Blackburn seat, but shortly after was elected in a [[1950 Brighouse and Spenborough by-election|by-election to the Yorkshire seat of Brighouse and Spenborough]]. In the reshuffle caused by the resignation of Sir [[Stafford Cripps]] as [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], he was appointed [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]], and held the post until the government lost the [[1951 United Kingdom general election|election of 1951]].\n\nIn opposition he became Chairman of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], and a member of the British parliamentary delegation to the [[Council of Europe]] from 1955, where he was elected in 1957 as vice-president and in April 1959 as President of the Consultative Assembly.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Dorothy May Watson<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p43421.htm#i434204 |title=Dorothy May Watson |website=The Peerage|publisher=Darryl Lundy|access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref> in 1931 and had two daughters: Valerie Hope Edwards, who married [[John Roper, Baron Roper|Baron Roper]], the Labour MP John Roper; and Margaret Elaine Edwards, who married Sir Christopher Jenkins,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-21981/version/1 |title=Jenkins, Sir (James) Christopher |website=Who's Who 2018 |access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref> [[Office of the Parliamentary Counsel (United Kingdom)#List of First Parliamentary Counsel|First Parliamentary Counsel]] 1994\u20131997.\n\n==Death==\nIn November 1959, in [[Strasbourg]] on Council of Europe business, he died suddenly of heart disease, aged 55. Then Labour leader, [[Hugh Gaitskell]], was quoted as saying that \"''his notable administrative gifts would have ensured him an important post in any future Labour government''\".\n\n==References==\n<references />\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n* Obituary, ''The Times'', 24 November 1959\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-edwards-2 |  John Edwards }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = Sir [[George Elliston]]<br /> and Sir [[W. D. Smiles]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Blackburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]]\n | with = [[Barbara Castle, Baroness Castle of Blackburn|Barbara Castle]]\n | years  = [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]\u2013[[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished<br /><small>(split into [[Blackburn East (UK Parliament constituency)|east]] and [[Blackburn West (UK Parliament constituency)|west divisions]])</small>\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Brighouse and Spenborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighouse and Spenborough]]\n  | years  = [[1950 Brighouse and Spenborough by-election|1950]]\u2013[[1960 Brighouse and Spenborough by-election|1959]]\n  | before = [[Frederick Cobb]]\n  | after  = [[Michael Shaw, Baron Shaw of Northstead|Michael Shaw]]\n}}\n{{s-npo|union}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = General Secretary of the [[Post Office Engineering Union]]\n  | years  = 1938\u20131947\n  | before = [[Charles Howard Smith (trade unionist)|Charles Howard Smith]]\n  | after  = [[Douglas Coward]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=President of the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]]|years=1959|before=[[Fernand Dehousse]]|after=[[Per Federspiel]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, John}}\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:British economists]]\n[[Category:General Secretaries of the Post Office Engineering Union]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Leaders of British trade unions]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Aylesbury]]\n[[Category:Politics of Blackburn with Darwen]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1950\u20131951]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1951\u20131955]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1955\u20131959]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1959\u20131964]]\n[[Category:People educated at Aylesbury Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary Secretaries to the Board of Trade]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of the Fabian Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2015}}\n{{more footnotes|date=October 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''Lewis John Edwards''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (27 May 1904 \u2013 23 November 1959) was a British university lecturer, [[trade union]] leader and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician.\n\n==Life and career==\nEdwards was born in [[Aylesbury]], the son of a railwayman, and educated at the [[Aylesbury Grammar School]]. After working for a bank, he studied for the priesthood at the [[College of the Resurrection|College of the Resurrection, Mirfield]], but decided his vocation lay outside the church. He then completed a degree in Economics at [[Leeds University]].\n\nHe became a staff tutor at the [[University of Leeds]] and lectured in economics for the [[Workers Educational Association]]. He was elected to [[Leeds City Council]], and after working in a university appointment in [[Birmingham]], he became secretary for adult education at [[Liverpool University]].\n\nWhile at Liverpool, he was elected general secretary of the [[Post Office Engineering Union]]. He was elected as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Blackburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]] in the [[United Kingdom]] [[1945 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1945]]. He became [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Stafford Cripps]] at the [[Board of Trade]], and then in 1947 he was made [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Ministry of Health]]. He carried through Parliament the [[National Assistance Act 1948]], which abolished the remaining parts of the [[Poor Law]], an achievement of which he was particularly proud.\n\nIn 1949 he returned to the Board of Trade as [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Board of Trade|Parliamentary Secretary]], supporting the President, [[Harold Wilson]]. In the [[1950 United Kingdom general election|election of 1950]] he lost his Blackburn seat, but shortly after was elected in a [[1950 Brighouse and Spenborough by-election|by-election to the Yorkshire seat of Brighouse and Spenborough]]. In the reshuffle caused by the resignation of Sir [[Stafford Cripps]] as [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], he was appointed [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]], and held the post until the government lost the [[1951 United Kingdom general election|election of 1951]].\n\nIn opposition he became Chairman of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], and a member of the British parliamentary delegation to the [[Council of Europe]] from 1955, where he was elected in 1957 as vice-president and in April 1959 as President of the Consultative Assembly.\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Dorothy May Watson<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p43421.htm#i434204 |title=Dorothy May Watson |website=The Peerage|publisher=Darryl Lundy|access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref> in 1931 and had two daughters: Valerie Hope Edwards, who married [[John Roper, Baron Roper|Baron Roper]], the Labour MP John Roper; and Margaret Elaine Edwards, who married Sir Christopher Jenkins,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-21981/version/1 |title=Jenkins, Sir (James) Christopher |website=Who's Who 2018 |access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref> [[Office of the Parliamentary Counsel (United Kingdom)#List of First Parliamentary Counsel|First Parliamentary Counsel]] 1994-1997.\n\n==Death==\nIn November 1959, in [[Strasbourg]] on Council of Europe business, he died suddenly of heart disease, aged 55. Then Labour leader, [[Hugh Gaitskell]], was quoted as saying that \"''his notable administrative gifts would have ensured him an important post in any future Labour government''\".\n\n==References==\n<references />\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n* Obituary, ''The Times'', 24 November 1959\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-edwards-2 |  John Edwards }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = Sir [[George Elliston]]<br /> and Sir [[W. D. Smiles]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Blackburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]]\n | with = [[Barbara Castle, Baroness Castle of Blackburn|Barbara Castle]]\n | years  = [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]\u2013[[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished<br /><small>(split into [[Blackburn East (UK Parliament constituency)|east]] and [[Blackburn West (UK Parliament constituency)|west divisions]])</small>\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Brighouse and Spenborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighouse and Spenborough]]\n  | years  = [[1950 Brighouse and Spenborough by-election|1950]]\u2013[[1960 Brighouse and Spenborough by-election|1959]]\n  | before = [[Frederick Cobb]]\n  | after  = [[Michael Shaw, Baron Shaw of Northstead|Michael Shaw]]\n}}\n{{s-npo|union}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = General Secretary of the [[Post Office Engineering Union]]\n  | years  = 1938\u20131947\n  | before = [[Charles Howard Smith (trade unionist)|Charles Howard Smith]]\n  | after  = [[Douglas Coward]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=President of the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]]|years=1959|before=[[Fernand Dehousse]]|after=[[Per Federspiel]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, John}}\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:British economists]]\n[[Category:General Secretaries of the Post Office Engineering Union]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Leaders of British trade unions]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Aylesbury]]\n[[Category:Politics of Blackburn with Darwen]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1950\u20131951]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1951\u20131955]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1955\u20131959]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1959\u20131964]]\n[[Category:People educated at Aylesbury Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary Secretaries to the Board of Trade]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of the Fabian Society]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1994-1997 \u2192 1994\u20131997", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Edwards_(English_Labour_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Alfred Dobbs", "text_new": "{{Hatnote|Not to be confused with [[Alf Dubs]], a Labour MP from 1979 to 1987}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix=\n|name=Alfred Dobbs\n|image=\n|office=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Smethwick (UK Parliament constituency)|Smethwick]]\n|predecessor=[[Roy Wise]]\n|successor=[[Patrick Gordon Walker]]\n|term_start=26 July 1945\n|term_end=27 July 1945\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1882|6|18|df=yes}}\n|birth_name= Alfred James Dobbs\n|birth_place=[[Bozeat]], [[Northamptonshire]], England\n|death_date= {{death date and age|df=yes|1945|7|27|1882|6|18}}\n|death_place= [[Doncaster]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n|nationality= [[British nationality law|British]]\n|party= [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n}}\n'''Alfred James Dobbs''' (18 June 1882 \u2013 27 July 1945) was a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician and [[trade unionist]]. He died in a car accident the day after being elected as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Smethwick (UK Parliament constituency)|Smethwick]]; his one day as an MP remains the shortest term served since the [[Second World War]].\n\n==Local politics and union career==\nDobbs was born in [[Bozeat]], [[Northamptonshire]].<ref name=\"NM\"/> He served as a [[Rushden]] Urban District Councillor between 1906 and 1910, although he moved to [[Leeds]] in 1909. There, he immediately took an interest in the Leeds branch of the [[National Union of Boot and Shoe Operatives]], becoming president of the branch in 1917. In March, 1919, he was elected to the Executive Committee of the Union.<ref name=\"NM\"/>\n\nIn local politics, Dobbs was elected as a [[City of Leeds|Leeds City]] Councillor from 1923 to 1929, then as [[Alderman]] in Leeds 1929\u201336 and was chairman the Housing Committee.<ref name=\"NM\"/>  Dobbs was Leader of Labour Group on [[Leeds City Council]]<ref name=\"HNDM\">{{cite news |title=M.P. Killed in Car Crash|work=Hartlepool Northern Daily Mail|date=28 July 1945 |accessdate=27 May 2016 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000378/19450728/027/0002 | via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> between 1931 and 1936 as well as a  [[Justice of the Peace|magistrate]].\n\nAfter his time at the Leeds City Council, Dobbs worked as National Organiser for the Shoe Union 1936\u201345. He was well known at senior levels of the Labour Party, a member of the [[National Executive Committee]] 1936\u201345 and Chair of the Labour Party 1942\u201343.<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite news |title=Swerved to Avoid Child, Killed|work=Northampton Mercury|date=3 August 1945 |accessdate=27 May 2016 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000732/19450803/019/0001 | via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nDobbs stood for Parliament on several occasions, in [[Altrincham (UK Parliament constituency)|Altrincham]] at the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929 general election]] and in [[Leeds North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds North East]] at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]] and [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 general elections]].<ref name=\"NM\"/>\n\n==Election and death==\nHe was elected as MP for [[Smethwick (UK Parliament constituency)|Smethwick]] in the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|Labour landslide of 1945]], defeating the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] incumbent, [[Roy Wise]]. However, having been elected on 26 July 1945, Dobbs was killed in a car accident the next day, 27 July 1945. Attempting to avoid a child, Dobbs' car was in collision with a military vehicle in [[Doncaster]],<ref name=\"HNDM\"/> and he was killed instantly. His passenger, Mrs. Elsie Marshall, was seriously injured and was brought  to the [[Doncaster Royal Infirmary]].<ref name=\"NM\"/> She died later in hospital.<ref name=\"AJ\">{{cite news |title=M.P. Swerved to Avoid Child\u2014Killed|work=[[Aberdeen Journal]] Mail|date=16 August 1945 |accessdate=27 May 2016 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000578/19450816/047/0004 | via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Although there have been occasions when MPs were elected posthumously, Dobbs' term was the shortest actually served since [[World War II]].\n\nHe was succeeded as MP for Smethwick by Labour's [[Patrick Gordon Walker]], who held the seat for the next 19 years.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United Kingdom MPs with the shortest service]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n* {{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig  |title=British parliamentary election results 1918-1949 |origyear=1969 |edition= 3rd |year=1983 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-06-X}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Smethwick (UK Parliament constituency)|Smethwick]]\n  | years  = [[United Kingdom general election|<small>26 July</small><br>1945]]\u2013<br>[[1945 Smethwick by-election|<small>27 July</small><br>1945]]\n  | before = [[Roy Wise]]\n  | after  = [[Patrick Gordon Walker]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title=Chair of the [[National Executive Committee|Labour Party]] | before=[[Walter Green (politician)|Walter Green]] | after=[[George Ridley (Labour politician)|George Ridley]] | years= 1942\u20131943}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dobbs, Alfred James}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:National Union of Boot and Shoe Operatives-sponsored MPs]]\n[[Category:People from Wellingborough]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Chairs of the Labour Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:English trade unionists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hatnote|Not to be confused with [[Alf Dubs]], a Labour MP from 1979 to 1987}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix=\n|name=Alfred Dobbs\n|image=\n|office=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Smethwick (UK Parliament constituency)|Smethwick]]\n|predecessor=[[Roy Wise]]\n|successor=[[Patrick Gordon Walker]]\n|term_start=26 July 1945\n|term_end=27 July 1945\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1882|6|18|df=yes}}\n|birth_name= Alfred James Dobbs\n|birth_place=[[Bozeat]], [[Northamptonshire]], England\n|death_date= {{death date and age|df=yes|1945|7|27|1882|6|18}}\n|death_place= [[Doncaster]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n|nationality= [[British nationality law|British]]\n|party= [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n}}\n'''Alfred James Dobbs''' (18 June 1882 \u2013 27 July 1945) was a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician and [[trade unionist]]. He died in a car accident the day after being elected as a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Smethwick (UK Parliament constituency)|Smethwick]]; his one day as an MP remains the shortest term served since the [[Second World War]].\n\n==Local politics and union career==\nDobbs was born in [[Bozeat]], [[Northamptonshire]].<ref name=\"NM\"/> He served as a [[Rushden]] Urban District Councillor between 1906 and 1910, although he moved to [[Leeds]] in 1909. There, he immediately took an interest in the Leeds branch of the [[National Union of Boot and Shoe Operatives]], becoming president of the branch in 1917. In March, 1919, he was elected to the Executive Committee of the Union.<ref name=\"NM\"/>\n\nIn local politics, Dobbs was elected as a [[City of Leeds|Leeds City]] Councillor from 1923 to 1929, then as [[Alderman]] in Leeds 1929\u201336 and was chairman the Housing Committee.<ref name=\"NM\"/>  Dobbs was Leader of Labour Group on [[Leeds City Council]]<ref name=\"HNDM\">{{cite news |title=M.P. Killed in Car Crash|work=Hartlepool Northern Daily Mail|date=28 July 1945 |accessdate=27 May 2016 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000378/19450728/027/0002 | via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> between 1931 and 1936 as well as a  [[Justice of the Peace|magistrate]].\n\nAfter his time at the Leeds City Council, Dobbs worked as National Organiser for the Shoe Union 1936-45. He was well-known at senior levels of the Labour Party, a member of the [[National Executive Committee]] 1936\u201345 and Chair of the Labour Party 1942\u201343.<ref name=\"NM\">{{cite news |title=Swerved to Avoid Child, Killed|work=Northampton Mercury|date=3 August 1945 |accessdate=27 May 2016 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000732/19450803/019/0001 | via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nDobbs stood for Parliament on several occasions, in [[Altrincham (UK Parliament constituency)|Altrincham]] at the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929 general election]] and in [[Leeds North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds North East]] at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]] and [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 general elections]].<ref name=\"NM\"/>\n\n==Election and death==\nHe was elected as MP for [[Smethwick (UK Parliament constituency)|Smethwick]] in the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|Labour landslide of 1945]], defeating the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] incumbent, [[Roy Wise]]. However, having been elected on 26 July 1945, Dobbs was killed in a car accident the next day, 27 July 1945. Attempting to avoid a child, Dobbs' car was in collision with a military vehicle in [[Doncaster]],<ref name=\"HNDM\"/> and he was killed instantly. His passenger, Mrs. Elsie Marshall, was seriously injured and was brought  to the [[Doncaster Royal Infirmary]].<ref name=\"NM\"/> She died later in hospital.<ref name=\"AJ\">{{cite news |title=M.P. Swerved to Avoid Child\u2014Killed|work=[[Aberdeen Journal]] Mail|date=16 August 1945 |accessdate=27 May 2016 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000578/19450816/047/0004 | via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Although there have been occasions when MPs were elected posthumously, Dobbs' term was the shortest actually served since [[World War II]].\n\nHe was succeeded as MP for Smethwick by Labour's [[Patrick Gordon Walker]], who held the seat for the next 19 years.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United Kingdom MPs with the shortest service]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n* {{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig  |title=British parliamentary election results 1918-1949 |origyear=1969 |edition= 3rd |year=1983 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-06-X}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Smethwick (UK Parliament constituency)|Smethwick]]\n  | years  = [[United Kingdom general election|<small>26 July</small><br>1945]]\u2013<br>[[1945 Smethwick by-election|<small>27 July</small><br>1945]]\n  | before = [[Roy Wise]]\n  | after  = [[Patrick Gordon Walker]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title=Chair of the [[National Executive Committee|Labour Party]] | before=[[Walter Green (politician)|Walter Green]] | after=[[George Ridley (Labour politician)|George Ridley]] | years= 1942\u20131943}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dobbs, Alfred James}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:National Union of Boot and Shoe Operatives-sponsored MPs]]\n[[Category:People from Wellingborough]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in England]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Chairs of the Labour Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:English trade unionists]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLocal politics and union career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: well-known \u2192 well known, 1936-45 \u2192 1936\u201345", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Dobbs"}
{"title_page": "KTM West Coast railway line", "text_new": "{{KTM West Coast Line|collapse=yes}}\nThe '''West Coast railway line''' runs from [[Padang Besar railway station]] close to the [[Malaysia\u2013Thailand border]] in [[Perlis]] (where it connects with the [[State Railway of Thailand]]) to [[Woodlands Train Checkpoint]] in [[Singapore]]. It is called the West Coast railway line because it serves the West Coast states of [[Peninsular Malaysia]].\n\nThe 1,151-kilometre line is busier than the [[KTM East Coast Line|East Coast railway line]] because the West Coast railway line handles a variety of passenger train services such as the [[KTM ETS]] services, the [[KTM Intercity]] services, the [[International Express]], the [[KTM Komuter]] in the [[Klang Valley]] and [[Greater Penang Conurbation|Greater Penang]], and freight trains. Of this total length, 759&nbsp;km is double-tracked and electrified.\n\nThe major stations on the line include [[KL Sentral]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Butterworth railway station|Butterworth]] in [[Butterworth, Penang]] and [[Johor Bahru Sentral railway station|JB Sentral]] in the south in [[Johor Bahru]].\n\n==Line network==\n===Main trunk line===\nThe West Coast main trunk line stretches from [[Padang Besar railway station|Padang Besar]] on the [[Malaysia-Thailand border]] to [[Woodlands Train Checkpoint]] in Singapore.\n\nThe main trunk line is double-tracked and [[Railway electrification in Malaysia|electrified]] from Padang Besar to [[Gemas railway station|Gemas]]. From Gemas to the Woodlands Train Checkpoint, the line is single-tracked and not electrified. Loops at stations allow trains to pass. Double tracking and electrification works are currently being carried out. \n\nThe West Coast railway line connects with the State Railway of Thailand at Padang Besar, while the East Coast line branches off at [[Gemas railway station|Gemas]].\n\n===Branch lines===\nThe West Coast railway line includes several branch lines from the main trunk line, namely:\n*Bukit Mertajam Junction to [[Butterworth railway station|Butterworth]]\n*Batu Junction to [[Batu Caves Komuter station|Batu Caves]]\n*Port Klang/Bangsar Junction to [[Port Klang Komuter station|Port Klang]] and [[West Port, Malaysia|Westport]], with further branch lines:\n**[[Subang Jaya station|Subang Jaya]] to [[Terminal Skypark Komuter station|Terminal Skypark]] at the [[Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah Airport|Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah (Subang) Airport]]\n**[[Port Klang Komuter station|Port Klang]] to Northport\n**Pulau Indah to various Wesport shipping terminals\n*Skudai Junction to the [[Port of Tanjung Pelepas]]\n*[[Kempas Baru railway station|Kempas Baru]] to [[Johor Port|Pasir Gudang]]\n\nThe Bukit Mertajam Junction to [[Butterworth railway station|Butterworth]], Batu Junction to [[Batu Caves Komuter station|Batu Caves]], Port Klang Junction to [[Port Klang Komuter station|Port Klang]] station, as well as the branch lines to [[Terminal Skypark Komuter station|Terminal Skypark]] and Northport are double tracked and electrified. \n\nThe line from [[Port Klang Komuter station|Port Klang]] to Westport and its shipping terminals, as well as the branch lines between Skudai Junction and the [[Port of Tanjung Pelepas]] and the [[Kempas Baru railway station|Kempas Baru]] and [[Johor Port|Pasir Gudang]] are single lines and not electrified.\n\nThere are also branch lines where the tracks exist but are not used for any service or closed are:\n*Between [[Tapah Road railway station|Tapah Road]] and [[Teluk Intan]] (abandoned and not connected to the main line)\n*Between [[Seremban railway station|Seremban]] and [[Port Dickson]]\n<!--*Between [[Tasek railway station|Tasek]] and [[Tanjung Rambutan railway station|Tanjung Rambutan]] To be removed as is a portion of the old main line that was abandoned after double tracking, and not connected to the new main line, never used and meant as branch line compared to Teluk Intan branch line\n  -->\nNone of these disused branch lines are double tracked nor electrified.\n\n===Stations===\n====Main Trunk Line====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"1\"  style=\"margin:auto; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:180px;\"|Station names\n! style=\"width:160px;\"|Serving cities\n! style=\"width:160px;\"|Major landmarks\n! style=\"width:300px;\"|Remarks\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"4\"|(Continue to [[Thai Railway]])\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Padang Besar railway station|Padang Besar]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Padang Besar, Malaysia|Padang Besar]], [[Perlis]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|ets}} [[KTM ETS|ETS Line]]<br>{{rint|my|n2}} [[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Padang Besar-Butterworth route]]\n|- \n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bukit Ketri railway station|Bukit Ketri]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Bukit Ketri, [[Perlis]]\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|n2}} [[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Padang Besar-Butterworth route]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Arau railway station|Arau]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Arau]], Perlis<br>[[Pulau Langkawi]], [[Kedah]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|ets}} [[KTM ETS|ETS Line]]<br>{{rint|my|n2}} [[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Padang Besar-Butterworth route]]\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Kodiang railway station|Kodiang]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Kodiang]], [[Kedah]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|n2}} [[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Padang Besar-Butterworth route]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Tunjang railway station|Tunjang]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Closed and demolished\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Anak Bukit railway station|Anak Bukit]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Anak Bukit]], [[Kedah]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|ets}} [[KTM ETS|ETS Line]]<br>{{rint|my|n2}} [[KTM Ko