ter;\"|{{rint|my|10}} {{KLRT line|10}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Batu Tiga Komuter station|Batu Tiga]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Batu Tiga]], [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Shah Alam Komuter station|Shah Alam]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Seksyen 19, [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Padang Jawa Komuter station|Padang Jawa]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Padang Jawa]], [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bukit Badak Komuter station|Bukit Badak]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Jalan Bukit Badak, [[Klang (city)|Klang]], [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Klang Komuter station|Klang]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Klang (city)|Klang]], [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Teluk Pulai Komuter station|Teluk Pulai]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Teluk Pulai, [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Teluk Gadong Komuter station|Teluk Gadong]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Teluk Gadong, [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Kampung Raja Uda Komuter station|Kampung Raja Uda]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Kampung Raja Uda, [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Jalan Kastam Komuter station|Jalan Kastam]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Jalan Kastam, [[Port Klang]], [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Port Klang Komuter station|Port Klang]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Port Klang]], [[Selangor]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|2}} {{KLRT line|2}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"4\"|(Continue to [[West Port, Malaysia|Westport]])\n|}\n\n====Bukit Mertajam Junction-Butterworth Branch Line====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"1\"  style=\"margin:auto; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:180px;\"|Station names\n! style=\"width:160px;\"|Serving cities\n! style=\"width:160px;\"|Major landmarks\n! style=\"width:300px;\"|Remarks\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"4\"|Bukit Mertajam Junction between Simpang Ampat and Tasek Gelugor stations (Continue to main West Coast Line)\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bukit Mertajam railway station|Bukit Mertajam]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bukit Mertajam]], [[Penang]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|n1}} [[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Bukit Mertajam-Padang Rengas route]]<br>{{rint|my|n2}} [[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Padang Besar-Butterworth route]]<br>{{rint|my|ets}} [[ETS Line]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bukit Tengah railway station|Bukit Tengah]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bukit Tengah]], [[Penang]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|n2}} [[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Padang Besar-Butterworth route]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Perai\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Perai]], [[Penang]]\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Freights only\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[butterworth railway station|Butterworth]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Butterworth, Penang]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Penang Bridge]], [[Port of Penang]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{rint|my|n2}} [[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Padang Besar-Butterworth route]]<br>{{rint|my|ets}} [[ETS Line]]\n|}\n\n==Services==\nThe West Coast railway line is served by a variety of train services:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railway.co.th/main/index_en.html|title=State Railway of Thailand}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ktmb.com.my/MapsAndRoute.html|title=Keretapi Tanah Melayu}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/you-can-now-take-a-single-seater-business-class-ktm-train-from-kl-to-perlis/|title=You Can Now Take a Single-Seater Business Class KTM Train from KL to Perlis! - WORLD OF BUZZ|last=Ong|first=Ryan|date=2019-09-29|website=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n*'''[[KTM Intercity]]'''\n**''Ekspres Rakyat Timuran'' between [[Tumpat railway station|Tumpat]] and [[Johor Bahru Sentral railway station|JB Sentral]]. ''(The route between Gemas and JB Sentral is part of the West Coast Line while the route between Gemas and Tumpat is on the East Coast Line)''\n**''Ekspres Selatan'' between [[Pulau Sebang/Tampin railway station|Pulau Sebang/Tampin]] and [[Johor Bahru Sentral railway station|JB Sentral]].\n**''Shuttle Tebrau'' between [[Johor Bahru Sentral railway station|JB Sentral]] and [[Woodlands Train Checkpoint]]\n*{{rint|my|ets}} '''[[KTM ETS]]'''\n**''Business Class'' (one of 6 coaches upgraded with free wifi, charging sockets, on board dining & single seats; and only stops at a few major stations)\n***Between [[Kuala Lumpur Sentral station|KL Sentral]] and [[Padang Besar railway station|Padang Besar]]\n**''ETS Platinum'' (express service that only stops at a few major stations)\n***Between [[KL Sentral]] and [[Butterworth railway station|Butterworth]]\n***Between [[KL Sentral]] and [[Padang Besar railway station|Padang Besar]]\n**''ETS Gold'' (stops at all major stations a few minor stations)\n***Between [[KL Sentral]] and [[Ipoh railway station|Ipoh]]\n***Between [[KL Sentral]] and [[Padang Besar railway station|Padang Besar]]\n***Between [[KL Sentral]] and [[Butterworth railway station|Butterworth]]\n***Between [[Gemas railway station|Gemas]] and [[Butterworth railway station|Butterworth]]\n***Between [[Gemas railway station|Gemas]] and [[Padang Besar railway station|Padang Besar]]\n**''ETS Silver'' (stops at all stations)\n***Between [[KL Sentral]] and [[Ipoh railway station|Ipoh]]\n*{{rint|my|ktmkomuter}} '''[[KTM Komuter]]'''\n**{{rint|my|1}} ''[[Seremban Line]]'' between [[Batu Caves Komuter station|Batu Caves]] and [[Pulau Sebang/Tampin railway station|Pulau Sebang/Tampin]].\n**{{rint|my|2}} ''[[Port Klang Line]]'' between [[Tanjung Malim railway station|Tanjung Malim]] and [[Port Klang Komuter station|Port Klang]].\n**{{rint|my|10}} ''[[Skypark Link]]'' between [[KL Sentral]] and [[Terminal Skypark Komuter station|Terminal Skypark]].\n**{{rint|my|n1}} ''[[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Bukit Mertajam-Padang Rengas route]]'' between [[Bukit Mertajam railway station|Bukit Mertajam]] and [[Padang Rengas railway station|Padang Rengas]].\n**{{rint|my|n2}} ''[[KTM Komuter Northern Sector|Padang Besar-Butterworth route]]'' between [[Padang Besar railway station|Padang Besar]] and [[Butterworth railway station|Butterworth]].\n*'''[[International Express]]''' between [[Padang Besar railway station|Padang Besar]] and [[Bangkok|Bangkok's]] [[Hua Lamphong Railway Station]]\n\n==History==\nThe West Coast railway line was developed in stretches between 1885 with the opening of the Taiping-Port Weld Line, and 1932 when the line opened up to {{rws|Tanjung Pagar}}, thus spanning the entire west coast of Peninsular Malaysia from {{rws|Padang Besar}} on the [[Malaysia-Thailand Border|Malaysia-Thai border]] to Singapore. The line began with the construction of branches linking coastal ports with inland tin mining areas before they were gradually linked up by the main truck line running through the interior of the West Coast states of Peninsular Malaysia.\n\nThe latest new lines to be built were the branch lines to [[West Port, Malaysia|West Port]], [[North Port, Malaysia|North Port]], [[Tanjung Pelepas]], [[Pasir Gudang]] and the [[North Butterworth Container Terminal]]. The trunk line had also seen sections becoming disused, abandoned or even removed, with the latest being the closure and subsequent removal of the southernmost stretch of track between the [[Woodlands Train Checkpoint]] and {{rws|Tanjong Pagar}} in 2011.\n\n==Projects==\n\n===Gemas\u2013Johor Bahru electrification and double-tracking===\nAfter many years of announcements about the intention to upgrade the final stretch of single track of the West Coast Line, the Government began the public display exercise for the Gemas\u2013Johor Bahru electrification and double-tracking project on 27 October 2015. The public display exercise, required for all development of new railways under Section 84 of Malaysia's Land Public Transport Act 2010, will run until 27 January 2016.\n\nAccording to documents on display to the public, construction is expected to begin in 2016 and be completed in 2021.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mot.gov.my/my/projek-pembangunan/projek-pembangunan-rel/projek-gemas-jb| title=(untitled)| website=Portal Ramsi Kementerian Pengangkutan; Ministry of Transport}} {{dead link|date=November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe length of the line to be electrified and double-tracked is 197&nbsp;km between Chainage 563.040 at [[Gemas]] dan Chainage 754.180 at [[Johor Bahru]]. The project includes the construction of 11 stations at {{rws|Segamat}}, {{rws|Genuang}}, {{rws|Labis}}, {{rws|Bekok}}, {{rws|Paloh}}, {{rws|Kluang}}, {{rws|Mengkibol}}, {{rws|Rengam}}, {{rws|Layang-Layang}}, {{rws|Kulai}} and {{rws|Kempas Baru}}, and 3 future stations at {{rws|Tenang}}, {{rws|Chamek}} and {{rws|Senai}}. The upgraded line is supposed to cater for at least 22 services daily involving [[KTM ETS]], [[KTM Intercity]] and shuttle train services.\n\nThe documents displayed also stated that the electrification for the stretch will have the same specifications as that of the Seremban-Gemas stretch, name at 25\u00a0kV AC 50&nbsp;Hz single phase and supplied via an overhead catenary. Train operations for this stretch will be integrated with the Train Control Centres at KL Sentral and Gemas. The design speed for the tracks is 160&nbsp;km/h.\n\nOn 11 December 2015, the Chinese company [[China Railway Construction Company]] (CRCC) has been awarded to build the Gemas\u2013Johor Bahru electrification and double-tracking project.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Rail transport in Malaysia}}\n{{Klang Valley train stations}}\n{{Kunming\u2013Singapore railway}}\n\n{{coord missing|Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:railway lines in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Metre gauge railways in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:railway lines opened in 1885]]\n[[Category:1885 establishments in British Malaya]]\n", "name_user": "Draco97", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KTM_West_Coast_railway_line"}
{"title_page": "K\u00f8bmagergade", "text_new": "{{Infobox street\n| name            = K\u00f8bmagergade\n| native_name     = \n| image           = K\u00f8bmagergade, Copenhagen.jpg\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = K\u00f8bmagergade in 2014\n| former_names    = \n| location        = [[Indre By]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| postal_code     = 1150\n| length_m        =  510\n| width           =\n| metro                   = [[N\u00f8rreport station|N\u00f8rreport]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|40|50.88|N|12|34|38.28|E}}\n}}\n'''K\u00f8bmagergade''' is a pedestrian shopping street in the Old Town of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It connects [[Amagertorv]] on [[Str\u00f8get]] to [[N\u00f8rreport station]], although the last section, north of [[Kultorvet]], is part of Frederiksborggade, which continues on the other side of the railway station.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Lille K\u00f8bmagergade (Gedde).png|thumb|150px|Lolle K\u00f8bmagergade as seen on [[Gedde's maps of Copenhagen]] from 1757 ]] \n[[Image:Den kongelige Porcel\u00e6nsfabrik.jpg|thumb|150px|left|The Royal Porcelain Manufactury]]\nThe history of the street dates back to about 1200 when it was part of the main route between [[Roskilde]] and the small settlement [[Gammel Strand|Havn]], which was a hub for crossings to [[Amager]] and [[Scania]]. Between 1380 and 1463, documents refer to the street as Bj\u00f8rnebrogade. It later became known as Ki\u00f8dmangergade after the butchers who had their stalls along the street. Kj\u00f8dmanger (\"meatmonger\") is an old Danish word for butcher. The meat market later moved to [[Skindergade]] but the name stuck with to the street, although it later changed to Kj\u00f8bmagergade and then K\u00f8bmagergade. The form Kj\u00f8dmagergade is first known from 1595 although the old form Kj\u00f8dmagergade is still seen in documents from 1656.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kobenhavnshistorie.dk/bog/kko/k/kko_k-37.html|title=K\u00f8bmagergade|language=Danish|publisher=Selskabet for K\u00f8benhavns Historie|accessdate=2013-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004225658/http://www.kobenhavnshistorie.dk/bog/kko/k/kko_k-37.html|archive-date=2013-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe North Gate was moved to the northern end of the street in 1671.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indenforvoldene.dk/noerregade.html|title=N\u00f8rregade|language=Danish|publisher=indenforvoldene.dk|accessdate=2013-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215330/http://www.indenforvoldene.dk/noerregade.html|archive-date=2013-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Royal Copenhagen|Royal Porcelain Manufactury]] was founded in the street in 1775. The company left the street after being taken over by [[Aluminia]], joining the new owners at their site in [[Frederiksberg]] (now [[Porcel\u00e6nshaven]]) in 1884.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/DAEF%20400-499/Side_437_Nits_-_Nobe.html|title=Erhvervsdrivende, deres ansatte og andre personligheder.|language=Danish|publisher=coneliand.dk|accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref>\n\nK\u00f8bmagergade was pedestrianised in 1973 following the successful pedestrianisation of Str\u00f8get in the early 1960s.<ref name=publicspaces >{{cite book|last1=Gehl|first1=Jan|last2=Gemz\u00f8e|first2=Lars|title=Public Spaces, Public Life, Copenhagen|year=1996|url=|isbn=877 407 305 2|publisher=The Danish Architectural Press and the Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts|page=14}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings and residents==\nBuildings in the street include the [[Rundet\u00e5rn|Round Tower]], [[Regensen]] and the [[M\u00f8inichen Mansion]], now K\u00f8bmagergade Post Office with the Post & Tele Museum.\nNo. 42 is the former [[Varehuset Messen]] department store which opened in 1895. The building was designed by [[Emil Blichfeldt]] and is topped by a [[Hermes]] statue by [[Julius Schultz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indenforvoldene.dk/koebmagergade%2042%20-%20klareboderne%201.html|title=K\u00f8bmagergade 42/Klareboderne 1|language=Danish|publisher=indenforvoldene.dk|accessdate=2013-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004221938/http://www.indenforvoldene.dk/koebmagergade%2042%20-%20klareboderne%201.html|archive-date=2013-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> It is now used by Niels Brock Copenhagen Business College whose main building is on Kultorvet.\n\n==Public art, monuments and memorials==\n[[Image:Ewald & Wessel Monument.jpg|thumb|150px|The monument to Peter Herman Wessel and Johannes Ewald]]\nNext to the Round Tower stands a monument to the two 18th-century poets [[Peter Herman Wessel]] and [[Johannes Ewald]]. The monument was designed by [[Otto Evens]] and installed in 1879. It features reliefs in bronze of the two poets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kk.sites.itera.dk/apps/kk_monumenter/index.asp?lang=uk&mode=detalje&id=134|title=Monument to the Poets Peter Herman Wessel and Johannes Ewald|publisher=Copenhagen Municipality|accessdate=2014-01-13}}</ref>\n\n==Shopping==\nThe Illum Department Store is located on the corner of K\u00f8bmagergade and Str\u00f8get. The Arnold Busch chain of book stores has a two-storey flagship store at the Round Tower. International brands and chains with flagship stores in the street include [[Esprit Holdings|Esprit]], [[Abercrombie & Fitch]], [[Vans]] and [[Diesel (brand)|Diesel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aok.dk/shopping/amerikansk-kaede-er-aabnet-paa-koebmagergade|title=Amerikansk k\u00e6de er \u00e5bnet p\u00e5 K\u00f8bmagergade|language=Danish|publisher=Berlingske|accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nThe opening scene of [[Herman Bang]]'s impressionist 1887 novel ''Stucco'' is set on K\u00f8bmagergade just before the shops closes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straederne.dk/images/Gl-blade/2008/pdf/strderne20feb.lilleny.pdf|title=Stuk - den f\u00f8rste rigtige k\u00f8benhavnerroman|author=Lotte Frederiksen|website=straederne.dk|accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"170px\" heights=\"140px\">\nImage:K\u00f8bmagergade 22 - K\u00f8bmagerhus.jpg|No 22. 22. K\u00f8bmagerhus from 1898\nImage:Messen - 42 K\u00f8bmagergade.jpg|No. 42: Varehuset Messen\nImage:Regensen (Copenhagen).jpg|[[Regensen]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[H. H. Thiele]]\n* [[Vilhelm Prior]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|K\u00f8bmagergade}}\n* [https://ing.dk/artikel/strom-skabte-det-moderne-kobenhavn-78011 Source]\n* [https://www.kbh.dk/blogs/historien-bag-vejnavnet-derfor-hedder-det-koebmagergade Source]\n\n{{coord|55.6808|N|12.5773|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kobmagergade}}\n[[Category:Pedestrian streets in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Shopping streets in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Streets in Copenhagen]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox street\n| name            = K\u00f8bmagergade\n| native_name     = \n| image           = K\u00f8bmagergade, Copenhagen.jpg\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = K\u00f8bmagergade in 2014\n| former_names    = \n| location        = [[Indre By]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| postal_code     = 1150\n| length_m        =  510\n| width           =\n| metro                   = [[N\u00f8rreport station|N\u00f8rreport]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|40|50.88|N|12|34|38.28|E}}\n}}\n'''K\u00f8bmagergade''' is a pedestrian shopping street in the Old Town of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It connects [[Amagertorv]] on [[Str\u00f8get]] to [[N\u00f8rreport station]], although the last section, north of [[Kultorvet]], is part of Frederiksborggade, which continues on the other side of the railway station.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Lille K\u00f8bmagergade (Gedde).png|thumb|150px|Lolle K\u00f8bmagergade as seen on [[Gedde's maps of Copenhagen]] from 1757 ]] \n[[Image:Den kongelige Porcel\u00e6nsfabrik.jpg|thumb|150px|left|The Royal Porcelain Manufactury]]\nThe history of the street dates back to about 1200 when it was part of the main route between [[Roskilde]] and the small settlement [[Gammel Strand|Havn]], which was a hub for crossings to [[Amager]] and [[Scania]]. Between 1380 and 1463, documents refer to the street as Bj\u00f8rnebrogade. It later became known as Ki\u00f8dmangergade after the butchers who had their stalls along the street. Kj\u00f8dmanger (\"meatmonger\") is an old Danish word for butcher. The meat market later moved to [[Skindergade]] but the name stuck with to the street, although it later changed to Kj\u00f8bmagergade and then K\u00f8bmagergade. The form Kj\u00f8dmagergade is first known from 1595 although the old form Kj\u00f8dmagergade is still seen in documents from 1656.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kobenhavnshistorie.dk/bog/kko/k/kko_k-37.html|title=K\u00f8bmagergade|language=Danish|publisher=Selskabet for K\u00f8benhavns Historie|accessdate=2013-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004225658/http://www.kobenhavnshistorie.dk/bog/kko/k/kko_k-37.html|archive-date=2013-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe North Gate was moved to the northern end of the street in 1671.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indenforvoldene.dk/noerregade.html|title=N\u00f8rregade|language=Danish|publisher=indenforvoldene.dk|accessdate=2013-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215330/http://www.indenforvoldene.dk/noerregade.html|archive-date=2013-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Royal Copenhagen|Royal Porcelain Manufactury]] was founded in the street in 1775. The company left the street after being taken over by [[Aluminia]], joining the new owners at their site in [[Frederiksberg]] (now [[Porcel\u00e6nshaven]]) in 1884.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coneliand.dk/Danmarks%20aeldste%20forretninger/DAEF%20400-499/Side_437_Nits_-_Nobe.html|title=Erhvervsdrivende, deres ansatte og andre personligheder.|language=Danish|publisher=coneliand.dk|accessdate=2013-07-22}}</ref>\n\nK\u00f8bmagergade was pedestrianised in 1973 following the successful pedestrianisation of Str\u00f8get in the early 1960s.<ref name=publicspaces >{{cite book|last1=Gehl|first1=Jan|last2=Gemz\u00f8e|first2=Lars|title=Public Spaces, Public Life, Copenhagen|year=1996|url=|isbn=877 407 305 2|publisher=The Danish Architectural Press and the Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts|page=14}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings and residents==\nBuildings in the street include the [[Rundet\u00e5rn|Round Tower]], [[Regensen]] and the [[M\u00f8inichen Mansion]], now K\u00f8bmagergade Post Office with the Post & Tele Museum.\nNo. 42 is the former [[Varehuset Messen]] department store which opened in 1895. The building was designed by [[Emil Blichfeldt]] and is topped by a [[Hermes]] statue by [[Julius Schultz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indenforvoldene.dk/koebmagergade%2042%20-%20klareboderne%201.html|title=K\u00f8bmagergade 42/Klareboderne 1|language=Danish|publisher=indenforvoldene.dk|accessdate=2013-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004221938/http://www.indenforvoldene.dk/koebmagergade%2042%20-%20klareboderne%201.html|archive-date=2013-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> It is now used by Niels Brock Copenhagen Business College whose main building is on Kultorvet.\n\n==Public art, monuments and memorials==\n[[Image:Ewald & Wessel Monument.jpg|thumb|150px|The monument to Peter Herman Wessel and Johannes Ewald]]\nNext to the Round Tower stands a monument to the two 18th-century poets [[Peter Herman Wessel]] and [[Johannes Ewald]]. The monument was designed by [[Otto Evens]] and installed in 1879. It features reliefs in bronze of the two poets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kk.sites.itera.dk/apps/kk_monumenter/index.asp?lang=uk&mode=detalje&id=134|title=Monument to the Poets Peter Herman Wessel and Johannes Ewald|publisher=Copenhagen Municipality|accessdate=2014-01-13}}</ref>\n\n==Shopping==\nThe Illum Department Store is located on the corner of K\u00f8bmagergade and Str\u00f8get. The Arnold Busch chain of book stores has a two-storey flagship store at the Round Tower. International brands and chains with flagship stores in the street include [[Esprit Holdings|Esprit]], [[Abercrombie & Fitch]], [[Vans]] and [[Diesel (brand)|Diesel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aok.dk/shopping/amerikansk-kaede-er-aabnet-paa-koebmagergade|title=Amerikansk k\u00e6de er \u00e5bnet p\u00e5 K\u00f8bmagergade|language=Danish|publisher=Berlingske|accessdate=2013-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nThe opening scene of [[Herman Bang]]'s impressionist 1887 novel ''Stucco'' is set on K\u00f8bmagergade just before the shops closes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straederne.dk/images/Gl-blade/2008/pdf/strderne20feb.lilleny.pdf|title=Stuk - den f\u00f8rste rigtige k\u00f8benhavnerroman|author=Lotte Frederiksen|website=straederne.dk|accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"170px\" heights=\"140px\">\nImage:Copenhagen - K\u00f8bmagerhus).jpg|No 22. 22. K\u00f8bmagerhus from 1898\nImage:Messen - 42 K\u00f8bmagergade.jpg|No. 42: Varehuset Messen\nImage:Regensen (Copenhagen).jpg|[[Regensen]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[H. H. Thiele]]\n* [[Vilhelm Prior]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|K\u00f8bmagergade}}\n* [https://ing.dk/artikel/strom-skabte-det-moderne-kobenhavn-78011 Source]\n* [https://www.kbh.dk/blogs/historien-bag-vejnavnet-derfor-hedder-det-koebmagergade Source]\n\n{{coord|55.6808|N|12.5773|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kobmagergade}}\n[[Category:Pedestrian streets in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Shopping streets in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Streets in Copenhagen]]\n", "name_user": "Hjart", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Copenhagen - K\u00f8bmagerhus).jpg\u2192File:K\u00f8bmagergade 22 - K\u00f8bmagerhus.jpg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C3%B8bmagergade"}
